Yeah that’s the cleaner execution. You were overcomplicating it in my earlier framing.
The real mechanic is simpler and actually more publishable:
Cards are printed in the back of the book. Perforated or on card stock insert pages. Each card features art pulled directly from that book’s spreads — so the Lapras card looks like the Cerulean City watercolor spread it came from. The art style of the location becomes the card’s visual identity. That’s a genuinely novel collectible — you can’t get a watercolor Lapras card anywhere else. It’s exclusive to owning the book.
Why this is better than the unlock mechanic:
The unlock idea adds friction and infrastructure — QR codes, apps, redemption systems. Publishers hate that. It requires ongoing maintenance, server costs, and TPC would need to coordinate with the TCG digital team. Too many moving parts for a children’s book pitch.
Perforated cards in the back of the book is simple, physical, proven. Cereal boxes have done it for 70 years. The Pokémon card is already a known object. You’re just delivering it through a new channel with exclusive art.
How it actually works:
Back of each book has 6-10 perforated card stock pages. Each card corresponds to a Pokémon featured in that book’s spreads. The art is location-specific — Gengar card looks like the Lavender Town spooky watercolor spread. Charizard card looks like the Cinnabar Island dramatic illustration. Cards are promo-legal, meaning TPC designates them as official promo cards outside the main TCG set — they already do this for McDonald’s Happy Meals, Pokémon Center exclusives, special events.
The pitch line becomes:
Each book includes exclusive promo cards featuring art from that region’s spreads — collectibles you can’t get anywhere else.
That’s it. Clean, physical, no app required, directly in TPC’s existing promo card infrastructure.
